Goëry (?-18 September, 643), also called Goeric, Goericus, Goéry or Abbon was bishop of Metz.He was probably born between 565 and 575 Butler's Lives of the Saints p182 Alban Butler, Paul Burns, 1995 ISBN 0860122581. As Sigebaud the 34 bishop of Metz, he is from the family Ansbertina of Albi Archdiocese of Albi (Albia). Goyau, G. (1907) In The Catholic Encyclopedia. New York: Robert Appleton Company. For some hagiographers Goëri was the son of Gamardus, himself brother of Ansbert the senator and the grandson of Tonantius FerreolusHistoire of the political institutions of old France, volume 6, book II, p144 Fustel de Coulanges, Paris, Hachette, 1907.He was married and had two daughters. He was first a soldier and then will become governor of the AlbigeoisSaint Goëric Daniel Bigerel, Circle local studies of Houdemont. He is said to have been an officer with the king Dagobert I, but this poses problems of date since Dagobert becomes king in 629, after the accession of Goëri to the episcopal throne. It appears, however, in the will of the king of 636, under the name of Abbo. Become blind he would have been miraculously healed by the affixing of a stone, who collects the blood of the martyr Stephen (another tradition wants it to be on a pilgrimage with his uncle Arnoul Metz bishop of the cathedral dedicated to this saint
http://histoire.egliseepinal.com/page18.html). Thank God, he made use of his wealth to build a church at Metz, dedicated to St. Peter, to the Images (extinct in 1755)He was ordained a priest by Arnoul of Metz, to which it succeeded at 627 (625 or 629) to the office of bishop of Metz.As bishop, he transferred the relics of his predecessor in 641 in the church of the Holy Apostles in Metz. He also built the church of Saint-PierreDictionnaire of the department of the Moselle p292, Claude Philippe de Viville 1817, and the abbey of Epinal for his two daughters, Precia and Victorina.He maintained a correspondence with the bishop of Cahors Didier, some of whose letters has come down to us.He died in 644 (642 or the September 19, 647).
Catholic Saint, he is celebrated on 19 September. On June 21, 984Orbituitaire of the chapter : "(Trans)latio (Santi Goerici M)etensis episcopi " to the date of the eleventh of the kalends of July, that is to say, 21 June, his relics (except his head) have been transferred to the abbey of Saint-Symphorien up to Épinal to consecrate the abbey, founded a chapel dedicated to the saint as early as the VII siècleB. Houbot, Foundation and origins of the city of Épinal, Bulletin de la Société Lorraine Local Studies, 1976.. On this occasion had come the 27th or 28th bishop of Metz, and Gerard of Toul, to the abbey founded by his predecessor and the other as the Spinal was in his diocese. This event is locally commemorated on April 15, because there had been a miracle reported by Wildric to 1030; the boxes containing the relics of Goéry was ill-prepared and did not lead to the battlements, a reduction miraculous made that the operation was successful.
He is the patron saint of the city of Epinal, which was an important place of pilgrimage in the Middle Ages. An array of 1725 is preserved in the basilica of Saint-Maurice d'épinal represents Goëri surrounded by his two fillesFiche PM88000283sur the base Palissy.
